4 by knockout.\u003c/em\u003e","citation":""},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"02f66d9a-8b87-4207-b729-ed8d484c7e2d","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"By the end of 1935, Louis had defeated former heavyweight champions Primo Carnera, a symbolic victory over \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/benito-mussolini\"\u003eBenito Mussolini\u003c/a\u003e’s Italy, and Max Baer. But on June 19, 1936, he faced off with German boxer Max Schmeling, who knocked Louis out in the 12th round. Louis had experienced his first professional defeat, but he was determined to get a rematch.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"fe4dbb0d-7454-4195-94b0-f825dcd54b49","name":"corpnews-blocks/story-grid","attributes":{"posts":"[{\"id\":24070,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/joe-louis-max-schmeling-match\",\"title\":\"When Joe Louis Boxed Nazi Favorite Max Schmeling\",\"type\":\"story\"},{\"id\":27227,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/jackie-robinson-color-barrier-baseball\",\"title\":\"Jackie Robinson’s Battles for Equality On and Off the Baseball Field\",\"type\":\"story\"}]","className":"is-style-2-col","preview":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"8b418929-6aef-46b3-9798-368a3fb4ece3","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Joe Louis vs. Max Schmeling","level":2,"id":"section_4"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"cae8a8f2-8a0f-490a-a098-5e48356e8793","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"On June 22, 1938, Joe Louis and Max Schmeling, whom \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/adolf-hitler-1\"\u003eAdolf Hitler\u003c/a\u003e saw as an exemplary representative of the Aryan race, faced off in front of 70,043 fans in a dramatic rematch at Yankee Stadium. Louis defeated Schmeling in two minutes and four seconds, knocking him out in the first round. The press seized on the victory as symbolic of the victory of democracy over fascism.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"6091b320-8929-4332-bf7c-ba2d8b598b00","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Joe Louis and The Military","level":2,"id":"section_5"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a771db7a-d9a1-4154-b65f-3d9bd35a089d","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"As \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history\"\u003eWorld War II\u003c/a\u003e raged on, Joe Louis donated almost $100,000 worth of his earnings to Army and Navy relief societies. In 1942, he joined the Army. During his service he was part of over 96 boxing exhibitions and performed for over two million members of the military. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"8896d205-a8fa-42d6-8967-f25c65001c5d","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"After an eleven-year and eight-month streak as heavyweight champion—the longest run in history at the time—Joe Louis retired form boxing on March 1, 1949. His retirement would be short-lived.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"1e21db61-c4ee-42bd-a2b9-db7cd7301e93","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Joe Louis Comes Out of Retirement","level":2,"id":"section_6"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"e55759ff-f8e2-413a-9e23-150c6ba8d95c","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"With the IRS coming after him for not paying taxes, 37-year-old Joe Louis came out of retirement in 1951. He was successful in his fight against Freddie Beshore on January 3, 1951, prompting excitement about a major comeback.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"68e97573-e3c6-4235-b460-ada5c1d22764","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Louis met his match when he faced off against 27-year-old Rocky Marciano, “the Brockton Blockbuster.” On October 26, 1951, the two entered the ring in New York’s Madison Square Garden. Rocky, who stood at 5’10” and weighed just 185 pounds, was one of the smallest champions in heavyweight division history, but he had youth on his side. Sports columnist Red Smith wrote of the match: "